original_dir = pathlib.Path("../Cat_dog_images/train")  # this extracts the train data 
new_base_dir = pathlib.Path("../Cat_dog_images/train_small")

def make_subset(subset_name, start_index, end_index):
    for category in ("cat", "dog"):
        dir = new_base_dir / subset_name / category
        os.makedirs(dir)
        fnames = [f"{category}.{i}.jpg" for i in range(start_index, end_index)]
        for fname in fnames:
            shutil.copyfile(src=original_dir / fname,
                            dst=dir / fname)

make_subset("train", start_index=0, end_index=1000)
make_subset("validation", start_index=1000, end_index=1500)
make_subset("test", start_index=1500, end_index=2500)

for image_batch, _ in train_dataset.take(1):

Image batch shape: (32, 180, 180, 3)
32: This is the batch size, meaning there are 32 images in the batch being processed at once.¶
180, 180: These are the dimensions of each image, indicating that each image is 180 pixels wide and 180 pixels tall.¶
3: This represents the number of color channels in each image. Since it's 3, the images are in RGB format (Red, Green, and Blue).¶

Definning the model¶

In [75]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)      # 32 neurones as there are 32 filters
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2)(x)
x = layers.Conv2D(filters=256, kernel_size=3, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)

import numpy as np

def get_features_and_labels(dataset):
    all_features = []
    all_labels = []
    for images, labels in dataset:
        preprocessed_images = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(images)
        features = conv_base.predict(preprocessed_images)
        all_features.append(features)
        all_labels.append(labels)
    return np.concatenate(all_features), np.concatenate(all_labels)

train_features, train_labels =  get_features_and_labels(train_dataset)
val_features, val_labels =  get_features_and_labels(validation_dataset)
test_features, test_labels =  get_features_and_labels(test_dataset)

We train our own top¶

In [91]:
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(5, 5, 512))  #  Defining and training the top, because the bottom layer is the same as it was trained on similar real world data so the feature detectors will be the same 
x = layers.Flatten()(inputs)
x = layers.Dense(256)(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)  # it says that the output doesn't rely on the best neurones, it sets their output to 0 in 50% of times or number of epoches, if there are 4 epoches , the output will not rely on the best neurones for 2 epoches so the other nuerones will always try to be better.
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

for name, model in models.items():
    try:
        if name == "feature_extraction":
            predictions = (model.predict(test_features) > 0.5).astype("int32")
            true_labels = test_labels
        else:
            predictions = (model.predict(test_dataset) > 0.5).astype("int32")
            true_labels = np.concatenate([y for _, y in test_dataset], axis=0)
        
        report = classification_report(true_labels, predictions, output_dict=True)
        results[name]["precision"] = report["1"]["precision"]
        results[name]["recall"] = report["1"]["recall"]
        results[name]["f1_score"] = report["1"]["f1-score"]
        
        print(f"Classification Report for {name}:\n{classification_report(true_labels, predictions)}")
    except ValueError as e:
        print(f"Error with model {name}: {e}")

Conclusions¶

Feature extraction is the best-performing approach, achieving the highest precision and recall.¶
Fine-tuning is close behind but may not add significant improvements over feature extraction.¶
Convnet from scratch has poor performance, reaffirming that pre-trained models are crucial for small or medium-sized datasets.¶
Data augmentation (green curve) requires careful tuning to improve performance.¶
